Date: 5 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: La Nacion, Associated Press Report, 5 Oct 2001 (Trans. by Mod.MPP)
[edited

Fear of Epidemic of Dengue Hemorrhagic Fever in Panama
------------------------------------------------------
PANAMA: The Panamanian health authorities fear that there will be an
epidemic of fatal dengue hemorrhagic fever and are beginning an intense
prevention campaign. The campaign includes fumigations and heavy fines of
between 10 and 5000 dollars [Panamanian for persons in whose households
they encounter standing water which can serve as breeding sites for the
_Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.
Since the beginning of this year, the authorities have detected 517 cases
of classic dengue fever and 3 of dengue hemorrhagic fever. In contrast,
during the year 2000, 300 cases of classic dengue fever and 3 of dengue
hemorrhagic fever were reported. The authorities are concerned by the
increase in cases of classical dengue fever in comparison with last year,
because this increase carries the possibility that there will be reports of
more cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever. [The risk of contracting dengue
hemorrhagic fever is increased when patients who have recovered from an
initial attack of dengue fever are exposed to infection by dengue virus of
a heterologous serotype. - Mod.CP
The health authorities and those of civil defense are undertaking intensive
operations of fumigation and campaigns on raising public awareness on the
need for elimination of standing water where the mosquito can reproduce.
The operations have been intensified in rural areas of the capital, where
the highest incidence of dengue fever has been reported.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
