[2
Date: 7 Oct 2001
From: Dr Reggie Cooke <r.cooke@virgin.net>

A Comment Related to the Current Dengue Fever Outbreak in Hawaii
----------------------------------------------------------------
The current unfortunate situation in Hawaii reminds me of a very good
synopsis of Peter Whelan's detailed account on how the Northern Territory
of Australia manages to be free of dengue fever, when neighboring tropical
Queensland gets occasional outbreaks (see: _Aedes_ mosquitoes imported -
Australia (NT) (03) 20000320.0390.)
When larvae of 2 species of mosquito were discovered by quarantine officers
in Darwin's shipping yard, in the water of cargo of mining equipment just
arrived from East Timor, a very aggressive spraying procedure ensued. All
artificial containers and premises in the vicinity were sprayed, and the
general area was "misted" and "fogged" by a residual insecticide ("ultra
low volume bioresmethrin insecticide") with agreement of all concerned.
This was followed up by strict quarantine procedures and increased egg trap
surveillance and larvae inspection of all artificial containers in the area
over a period of several months.
Other measures are adopted in other parts of the world! For example one of
the measures used by the government of El Salvador in the fight against
dengue-carrying mosquitoes, was to fine those who did not cooperate in the
destruction of breeding sites. A state emergency was declared, but in spite
of these, and other measures, there were almost 2000 cases of dengue
between Jan and Feb 2000, including 300 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever.
--
Dr Reggie Cooke
Minor Injury Unit
S.Tyrone Hospital
Dungannon, N.Ireland
<r.cooke@virgin.net>
