[3
Date: 5 Oct 2001 10:03:55 -0700 (PDT)
From: V. Cardenas <cardenas@u.washington.edu>

I find [the statement "All Hawaii residents... are being urged to keep
their properties free of sites where mosquitoes can breed" laughable.
My family lives in the Puna area of the Big Island and, as with the vast
majority of residents out there, obtains its household water by water
catchment. Most household water catchment supplies are kept covered, but
every household I have ever visited out there has at least a half a dozen
other uncovered catchment [containers used for watering plants, providing
drinking water for animals, etc. Given that Hilo is the wettest city (most
rainfall) in the United States, I wonder how feasible [that "pipe dream' is.
That said, I have informed my family of this emerging threat and am hoping
they take it seriously enough to further protect themselves against mosquitos.
--
Vicky Cardenas
Department of Epidemiology
University of Washington
<cardenas@u.washington.edu>
